Finding Optimal Time Offset



The program for finding optimal time offsets for events between spacecraft works by using a primary spacecraft to find events (Wind). I selected Wind because I used Wind to train the model, and the events found in Wind are consistent with events found by eye or independent spacecraft algorithms. I define an event discontinuity as a time where our model indicates a 95.00% probability the solar wind parameters corresponds to a 5σ discontinuity in a component of the magnetic field. Currently, the program finds 207 events using the Wind spacecraft to define an event between 2015/06/04-2017/09/24 (2.25 years). After the code finds an event, the code tries to match plasma and magnetic field parameters from the other three spacecraft (ACE, DSCOVR, and SOHO/CELIAS). Initially, the program uses a 60 minute search window to find the best time offset between the training spacecraft (Wind) and the pupil spacecrafts (ACE, DSCOVR, SOHO/CELIAS). The 60 minute window returns a rough time offset between the pupil and trainer spacecraft. Then pupil shifts to the trainer spacecraft and recomputes the time offset using a 30 minute window, which is the rough time offset. Then using the rough offset, the code iteratively solves a refined time offset. The refined time offset comes from 3 iterations of a 3/2 σ cut preceding/following the event time. The 3/2 squeezing ratio stems for considerable noise (perhaps physical) after a discontinuity. Therefore, the optimal time prefers agreement before the event rather than after. Finally, after 3 iterations the code computes the offset at the discontinuity point and uncertainty from the variation in time offsets in the window. Each refinement method uses Dynamic Time Warping (DTW), which finds the minimum cost between two similar time series. The results improve the χ2 results, and DTW preforms the analysis approximately a factor of 20 quicker than the χ2 meathod (20 seconds compared to 600 seconds per event).

Table Summary

Each table contains a row for each spacecraft with observations in the requested time period. Then each row contains 6 columns. The first column labels the spacecraft for a given row. Then next column (Obs. Time [UT]) gives the time of the "event" in the reference frame of the spacecraft. Offset is the offset in minutes from the Wind observation. P-val (plasma) is the p-val for a 5σ discontinuity at the reference Obs. time for a given spacecraft's measured plasma values. P-val (mag.) is the p-val for a 5σ discontinuity given at the reference Obs. time for a given spacecraft's measured magnetic field values. while an empty cell denotes using the magnetic field. Clicking on the spacecraft shows the DTW convergence as a function of iteration number for Finally, an X in Use Plasma Mod. means the minimization routine use the wind Speed to find the best match (deprecated functionality), the wide and refined windows.
